JOHANNESBURG - Matshela Koko has been given a stay of execution. The Labour Court will hand down judgment on the former Eskom CEOs job early in February. He approached the court on Friday after the power utility’s new board gave him an ultimatum to either resign within 24 hours or face being fired. READ: Hands off Koko, say lawyers He is accused of being implicated in the awarding of contracts worth R640-million to a company in which his stepdaughter owns shares. Koko's lawyers on Thursday told the Eskom board it had no right to remove him as he had been cleared of any wrongdoing. The disciplinary hearing that exonerated him of fraud and corruption charges was reportedly a sham. eNCA